This story could have had the epic unfolding of a true tale, a story unwound to the limits of knights, gunslingers, science fiction, and horror. Yet fell so short of the written word. The only way to tell this was the same story I read as  young man was because of the character names. The tale lost its heart. We now have a kinda of cool sci-fi story full of low grade action and no meaning.
I have been reading Stephen King since I was 7 years old. That is 40 years of truly being entertained by Mr. King(thank you) yet I was so excited to see this story come to life and was just so very disappointed. It could have been so much more. Please don't follow this series , let it stay written.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
For all those complaining about Idris Elba being cast as Roland Deschain, King himself seems perfectly happy with the decision, saying the following:

 "I love it [Elba]. I think he's a terrific actor, one of the best working in the business now. For me the character is still the character. It's almost a Sergio Leone character, like the Man with No Name. He can be white or black, it makes no difference to me. I think it opens all kind of exciting possibilities for the backstory."

So there you have it. If the character's creator, (the one person that understands that character more than anyone else in the world), is satisfied with the casting, we really can't complain, now can we? Besides, Idris Elba looks pretty fucking cool as a space cowboy.

Comment: The true genius of The Dark Tower series is how it literally ties together like half of all the King novels ever written.  Characters from The Stand (including King's favorite go to bad guy Randall Flagg), Hearts in Atlantis, Salem's Lot etc etc. are included throughout the seven novels.  An absolutely genius move on King's part financially, since to truly get the full force of the Dark Tower, you really did have to go back and read all of his older work that led up to this.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
Hmmm...I'm provisionally on-board, though with serious misgivings.  Idris Elba has the chops, though I'm not sure the presence, to pull-off Roland.  Jeffery Wright would have been a much better choice.  And while Matthew McConaughey certainly seems to check-off many of the boxes, he's just plain wrong for Randall Flagg.  I think an unknown actor with some sort of ephemeral, otherworldly quality would fit the bill.  As for Jake, if what we saw was any indication, they just plain fucked-up with him.  Big time.

As for the plot and world changes, I don't know man.  What they did to the story looks like it could be interesting, but it seems such an overhaul and simplification...I don't see how it could possibly do the original story justice.  Plus, I don't think the filmmakers understand it's a dying, worn-out _universe_, not just world, that Roland comes from.

I guess I'll just try to forget the books while watching this.  That seems to be about the only way there's any chance of enjoying movie adaptations about 95% of the time.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
I was skeptical as all hell when it was announced that a Black actor would play a character who I have known to be based on a White person (described as Clint Eastwood mixed with a little Stephen King by the author) since I first read the first part of a novel that would consume me for decades nearly thirty years ago, but after seeing the trailer, I think that I can deal with Mr. Elba. He is a very good actor and I think that he can pull off this role. I always imagined Matthew McConaughey as Eddie, but whatever. 

I know a lot of people are up in arms, but see if this makes sense to you - he's not Roland as you know him, he's an alternate Roland: the same, yet different. It's like James Bond - they're all James Bond, the same and yet different. 

I also like how they've handled the plot - instead of this being based on the books that we've read, this is (SPOILER ALERT!!) Roland's next reincarnation on his perhaps-not-any-longer eternal quest to save the Tower. 

I'm jazzed for this movie to come out and I'm hoping as much as anyone else that it's amazing. The characters and the world that we fell in love with while reading the series deserve nothing less than awesomeness.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
SPOILER ALERT!!!!!


:
:
:
"The finite mind cannot grasp the infinite..." - The Man In Black.  This has never been more true than now reading all the hate from (fans?) of King's work.  King himself warned us of this before the Coda at the end of the final Dark Tower book. He warns us not to continue reading. He warns us that nothing he writes within the Tower could possibly fulfill what great expectations we, (the constant reader) have for Roland at the Tower. But we insist. We are Tower junkies like Roland himself. So, King writes it because we MUST see what is at the Tower. And that is the point of the ending. WE are the reason Roland is thrust back to the beginning. In essence, WE the constant reader, we FORCE Roland into that Tower when King warned us to let it go. We did it anyway. 

Now...this time Roland has the horn. I believe that the horn represents hope. I believe that this being the final time around, Roland carries the horn as a symbol of hope. He will right the wrongs from the times before, hence NOT allow Jake to die in pursuit of the Tower. The horn will balance out Roland's obsession for the Tower, and he will make the right choices. In fact, an alternate ending may come of this, where Roland reaches the Dark Tower, is granted entry, but simply walks away. 

Take care of your Ka-tet, (the people in your life that matter most), and let go of the obsession which resonates from the Dark Tower. 

I thankee sai. Long days and pleasant nights.   <3

Comment:
Roland is described as not only looking like Clint Eastwood but also looking eerily like the author himself, Stephen King, who resides on the key world. Idris looks nothing like SK, Roland, nor Eastwood.

Roland is based on a real French paladin, does that imply that the original Roland, Charlemagne, and possibly Arthur Eld are also darker skinned? Its very likely this will never be addressed, as a fan of the books this is unacceptable, you cannot change the story and characters without it reflecting on the background canon and mythology.

\\


Back to the original Roland, his king was the aforementioned Charlemagne. In the year 1,000 A.D. the locals dug up Charlemagne's dead body, they feared that the Devil would rise up to Earth and it would be the battle of Armageddon, so they needed the dead king to fight and save the world. This is real history.

Rolands weapons and horn are based on the real Roland's; Durendal and Olifant. These were real, these are real, so to say that its a new universe and those things never happened or they happened in a different way is a cop out, it doesn't address the how or the why, just what happened much later.

\\

Odetta Holmes is also based a real person, if they change Roland then there is a good chance they will change, remove, or otherwise alter her character. This would be insulting to Odetta Holmes and the struggles she went through to realize in her various works of art and activism.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
It‚Äôs important to distinguish the movie franchise from the books. The movies are not a straight up adaption of the books, they are a sequel of sorts. 

SPOILER WARNING
SPOILER WARNING

At the end of DT7, Roland reaches the top of the Tower and is horrified to learn that he‚Äôs completed his journey many, many times before. The voice from the tower, which I presume to be Gan, says ‚ÄúThis is your promise that things may be different, Roland ‚Äì that there may yet be rest.‚Äù He is pushed through the doorway back to the beginning of his trek across the Mohaine Desert, but this time he has the Horn of Eld. This is significant, as the Horn of Eld is a symbol of Roland‚Äôs lineage, his purpose and his companions. He was destined to wind the horn as he made his way through Can-Ka-No-Rey (the field of roses at the base of the tower), but in the books, he loses it when his friend, Cuthbert, gets killed at the Battle of Jericho Hill.

Now Roland has the Horn of Eld, it means that everything can change. With the Horn of Eld, he may be less inclined to watch his ka-tet sacrifice themselves for his quest. This is why the trailer shows things that do not happen in the books. Jake doesn‚Äôt die to get to Mid-World, he finds a doorway, like he does in The Sailor arc of The Drawing of the Three, and I‚Äôm willing to bet that Roland doesn‚Äôt make the same choice as before when it comes down to saving Jake or finding the Tower.

I liked quite a lot about the trailer. I enjoyed seeing parts of Mid-World, the Mohaine Desert, Gilead and the portal. I liked the glow in Roland‚Äôs eyes and his guns when he fires. It‚Äôs a good compromise between the bombardier-blue eyes he has in the books, and it also highlights that Roland‚Äôs abilities aren‚Äôt entirely natural to new audiences. Roland looks badass in his outfit, but it does seem a little too pristine for someone who has spent a good chunk of time wandering across an inhospitable desert.

There were a few things I didn‚Äôt like. Jake shouldn‚Äôt have to explain the importance of the Tower to Roland, and Roland should need no encouragement to reach it. However, judging by the obvious ADR done on the dialogue, I do wonder whether that was added to the trailer to explain the basic story. Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment: For anyone unfamiliar with the original story this looks fantastic. For those who have read the books, yes, Roland should be white and yes, changing his race does have a significant impact on the story because of racial elements within it that will have to be changed. With that said, Idris is an amazing actor, and from the trailer, it looks like he has absolutely nailed the part, as well as anyone possibly could with physical traits that disagree with the author's description (and die-hards' preconceived notions) of the character. Every movie adaptation changes parts of the story, and as long as they are able to do this while keeping the feel and the overall plot somewhat true to the original (which remains to be seen) I don't think this is a problem. The only issue I have with it is possibly the motivation of the studio to cast Idris. If they cast him because they felt he was the best person for the job, and that casting him was worth the blowback from the picky fans and the changes that needed to be made to the story because of the expectation of a great performance from him, then I applaud them for taking a risk and not excluding him on the basis of race. If, on the other hand, they chose him _because_ he is black, to make a statement to those who try to make everything about race and to gain popularity from those who complain about racism where it doesn't exist, then I think it was a poor choice. Unfortunately, we may never know why they did it, and we will just have to wait and see how true to the source the movie ends up being, and whether it's still a solid movie despite its departure from its roots.

Comment: This looks fucking good! I can't wait to see it! I'm a huge fan of _The Dark Tower_ series. I read all 7 mainline novels _twice over_ and I enjoyed them even more the second time around. Any true fan of Stephen King will know that more than half of King's other novels and short stories are connected in some way or other to _The Dark Tower_ universe including _The Stand, Hearts in Atlantis, The Talisman, 'Salem's Lot, Insomnia_ and many others. The first movie should have been subtitled _The Gunslinger_ but I can live with that. As for changing Roland from white to black, that doesn't bother me in the slightest. So long as the movies stay true to the spirit of the books and are done well, I'm satisfied. Here's to at least 6 more movies after this, my fellow Constant Readers!

Anyone who has been following the news for this movie since it was pitched in 08 (maybe 09?) know then that this IS NOT A RENDITION OF THE ORIGINAL 7! Stephen King himself approved of Idris Elba being Roland, and has stated this movie is a continuation AFTER the 7th book.

Any fans of the original books KNOW what happens to Roland at the end of the seventh, and this movie takes place after the last sentence of the last book. King has even stated that Roland does posses the Horn of Eld, so that should be a sign to people what this one is about! 

We already know that Jake died once (though I think he died 3 times in the series all together), and we know that there is a nexus of multiple universes, and that at the end of the seventh book Susannah, Eddie, Jake (and it is implied Oy) have fading memories of what occurred. Comment:
I still can't wrap my mind around people thinking a screen adaptation should be exactly the same as the source material; whether it's comics, books, or previous films.

If it's exactly the same, then what's the point in even watching it?

Forget about the source of the story and judge the film based on the merits. To me the trailer looks pretty amazing.

Originally, I was a little curious about the casting choice for Roland. This was only because it would change the dynamic between he and a certain "drawn" individual. 

After some reflection, in the end, I don't think that it's really that detrimental to the story.

I hope the film does amazing. I want them to see it through to the end.

I still think I would have preferred it done as a series on HBO. With what they've done with "Ice and Fire" it seems that they could've done wonders with this as well.

Comment:
***SPOILERS***

This is not following the story lines from the book. If you finished the series, you should understand that and what the Horn of Eld means, and the last thing Gan says to Roland. This film is a continuation of the story, as Roland has been through the same cycle many, many times and always makes the wrong choices. 

This time around, he has the Horn of Eld, which is the last remaining artifact of All World That Was, aside from Roland's guns. It has the potential to change his path, as having the Horn means almost the entire timeline of the DT could have massive changes. This is why things are happening differently this time, and why this should almost certainly be Roland's last journey to the Tower before he is granted peace.

I figure it at least gives us the chance of a better ending for Roland. He deserves some redemption.

Comment:
If you read a lot of Stephen King's commentaries about the early days of him writing the series, it's fairly... bland. The first book (The Gunslinger) is also fairly bland compared to the others. I remember him reminiscing in one of his novels about various trips to a cabin in the summer during stormy weather, coming back to the original manuscript and touching it up to the final version of The Gunslinger that's available today. To those just watching this this trailer for the first time thinking for a great action movie, there's a TON of backstory and exposition that makes this universe come to life. This first movie is more of a re-imagining of the series than it is a faithful adaptation. This is coming from someone who has read the Dark Tower series once per year for the past 15 years.

That being said, this trailer has me fairly excited to see how this iconic series is re-imagined in our modern age. For reference, King started writing this series in the '70s and finally finished it in the early 2000's. I won't spoil things for anyone who hasn't read the series, but it goes on some fairly strange tangents (that sandwich sauce [book 6]). Thumbs up if you get that reference.

I feel like this movie is going to pay homage to the original novel (The Gunslinger), but take obvious liberties as it's "supposed" to take place after the novels (ie, Roland in NY before ever meeting Eddie). The whole novel series is fairly complex in its timelines. Feel free to debunk me on this.

I've wanted to see that sort of thing ever since I first heard that they might make movies of the Dark Tower books. Elba and Mcconaughey are both phenomenal actors so that is promising. Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
I really don't care about Roland being black or not. I really don't. I also like Idris Elba so I believe he's a fine character choice.

I really, really care about what appears to be a butchering of the main themes; mystery, despair, struggle against futility and destiny. I believe Roland (in the books), and by extension the entire series, to be an allegory to 'Do not go gentle into that good night'. 

This trailer feels like a teenage movie something akin to the Maze Runner etc. and that depresses me. Even if it is meant to be Roland on the next time around (an idea that would give loads of creative licence), it should still have the same atmospheric feel to it.

Obviously I can't be sure until the movie is released but as of right now, I'm worried that it has been dumbed-down and bastardised.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
0:39 Ah, that's funny. That's Timberline Lodge, a ski resort up on Mount Hood not far from where I live, though it's better known as the exterior of the Overlook Hotel in The Shining. The interiors were shot in a studio in England, and the real inside of Timberline is actually a lot cooler, though less mind-bending.

Fun fact - the Kubrick film used Room 237 instead of Room 217 from the book at the request of the lodge, because Timberline HAS no room 237, and they were afraid patrons would be afraid to sleep in a room associated with the movie. Ironic twist - room 217 is now Timberline's most requested suite.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment: As I'm currently reading (again) chapter VII of the Dark Tower series, after watching this trailer all I can say is: "What in the names of all Gods have you done, Hollywood?"  I mean, this looks very much like the typical film adaptation of a good book: You take the names of the main characters, some elements of the plot and then re-write the script completely differently so that the original book is nearly impossible to recognize. Yeah, we're been told that this is a sequel, so this is supposed to be the chapter VIII? Nope! From what I saw in this trailer I find basically no reason to go and see this film. For me, it just isn't a part of the Dark Tower story I have read and loved for so many years. It might be a good film. Even great. But Dark Tower? Nah, just and reflection of a dark tower in some insignificant parallel universe.

Comment:
My issue is that it seems they're condensing a wonderfully epic 7 book story into your run of the mill Hollywood piece of crap.

The story of Jake, Roland, and the Man in Black all happened in the book The Gunslinger.  Jake coming through the portal in the house doesn't happen until The Drawing of the Three.

For that matter, where the hell were Eddie and Susannah during all this?

I couldn't care less if they cast Jackie Chan as Roland of Gilead as long as they're faithful to the story. From what I've seen authenticity to the written work doesn't seem to be a high priority.

This would have worked much better as an HBO series.

When I first read these books some years ago, I found that though Mr. King might be a fine writer he knew little or nothing about firearms.   In the first few seconds of this trailer, we see the Gunslinger perform an impossible feat.
Somehow tossing a load of six cartridges into the air, and then moving his revolver to intercept them and perform a reload in mid-air, as it were.

Now this would be vastly unlikely under any circumstance, but the revolvers pictured are solid-frame single-action models which would NOT have a swing-open cylinder (were it not for CGI).   Rather, these weapons are loaded singly through a "loading gate" on the right side of the frame.
One round at a time.

Comment: "There are other worlds than this": For all of the haters (before the movie is even released!) please consider this when watching movie adaptations of Stephen King's books. He's already written the books; he's told "his" side of the story, so when he signs over movie rights he's allowing another creative entity to take from his work and tell the story from "their" point of view. If he's OK with it, so am I. And once I've seen the "new" point of view, it's then and only then, that I can judge it on its own merits or failings. Either way, I still have SK's masterpieces on my bookshelves to visit again and again, like dear old friends.

Comment:
Ok, here's my take. SPOILER ALERT BLANK SPACE



I had always assumed that after each restart things only changed a tiny bit. A myriad of tiny changes that will eventually lead to Roland's salvation. But that's always been my own assumption. What if things actually change A LOT each time? What if every time Roland goes after the tower it's almost a completely different story? Maybe Eddie and Susannah never even show up this time around, and are left to enjoy their reward for their actions in the last loop. This is a continuation after all, not an adaptation.

I'm just as interested to see how the Roland/Detta dynamic will now work as anyone else (if she shows up), but it's also true that not many actors are of a caliber to play Roland. Idris is definitely on a very short list. I'm very much looking forward to seeing what he does with the character.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment: I actually read what King said about what this movie is. If you read the series, this is not that movie. It's based on what happens after the end of the storyline of the books. Which, to my understanding, was a perfect loop. Adding to the underlying despair of the story and our hero. Since none of the movie studios had the balls to bring the actual story to film, King now tells us that Deschain is no longer stuck in a loop, but that things change with each run through. Leaving us with a hope that the series did not originally embody, and what is sure to be the bitter taste of sell out in our mouths. It is not a reboot like Star Trek, as King would have us believe. But a departure from his original storyline, which robs us of what made this story what it was in the first place. Replacing despair with a sense of hope that things can change for the better. That Roland mayhap find peace. And escape his fate. Leaving our hero to abandon his post, fading from memory. All the while, trying to dupe the reader into believing that everything works out for the best in the great finality of it all. An end that in no way justifies the means...

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
(HERE BE BOOK SPOILERS)

To people who accuse book fans of 'whining' about casting of Idris Elba as Roland: you obviously don't understand what it means for the plot of the adaptation. It means that even if Eddie Dean and Detta/Odetta/Susannah Walker appear in the sequel (and I think it's a safe bet they won't appear in this one), the relationship between members of the ka-tet will likely lose in complexity in nuance. It won't be fraught with racism, bigotry and mutual distrust (unless Susannah is cast as a white supremacist or something?).

Similarly, it does not bode well for the portrayal of Gunslinger himself. Let me remind you that the book Roland is as anti-heroic as they come: he is obsessed with reaching the Tower and does pretty horrific things in order to achieve his goal. I guess the jury's out on this, but I just can't see the black lead character murdering an entire village or betraying Jake and letting him fall to his death. It would be ironic if casting a black actor as Roland would lead to the whitewashing of his character.

I'm well aware that this movie isn't intended as a faithful adaptation but rather a sequel to the book series. But turning Dark Tower into a straightforward, good vs. evil, black vs. white (har har) fantasy romp still does not feel right to me.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
*SPOILERS AHEAD*

I'll hold my full judgments for the actual movie, but a huge part of TDT story arc is Roland turning from this ruthless person who seeks the tower for unknown reasons (?), into someone who comes to find kinship and loyalty in the Ka Tet he "draws" along the way. 

In fact, Roland's ruthless behavior in the first book is only overshadowed by The Man in Black. If you didn't understand his true motives, when you read the first chapter of the first book it feels like he brutally murders an unarmed farmer for nothing, and is forced to murder a woman who was cursed by the knowledge of the secret of death. Roland is partially insane because he gazed into Maerlyn's grapefruit for far too long. His sense of justice was distorted by it.   

 Idris Elba, on the other hand, seems like he's a hero fighting for "justice". I like his chiseled looks as much as the next person, but I agree that they should have made him look more haggard for this particular film. He feels like he exists outside of his decaying world, and is not a part of it.   

 Also, the interdimensionality gaps for characters like Jake have more horror and subtlety aspect in the books. I wish that they played Jake so that his visions were more disjointed and his behavior was more erratic before he resolved the break between worlds. I mean, the kid threw himself in front of a car and saw himself falling through a chasm of eternity. I don't just want other characters to feel like he was insane, I wish that the audience also felt  like HE could actually be totally insane. The confirmation of his "rantings" through an earthquake was a bit eyeroll for me.  

Roland is awful chatty in this film and provides a lot of exposition, and I understand why people like that in movies but...  

Thus far, it feels more like a straightforward action film with some jump scares interspersed and a DT flavor

Also, the tone seems kinda off... The books are horror/fantasy with a splash of sci fi. Marketing the movie as an action film just adds to the confusion. I wish this trailer were created more like a horror film and less like an action film. 

In fact, to me, right now, Westworld feels more like TDT than TDT feels like TDT 

I know trying to condense these books into something watchable has been a chore. I understand why they made certain choices and concede to big Hollywood on (probably a lot of) decisions. 

I just hope they did not forget the face of their fathers.

Spoilers and opinion





Looks good. I understand why people are upset but having just re-read the gunslinger, adapting just that book into a film I think would be so boring. The medium for that story fits in a book. This movie being a sequel to the whole book series is starting out more action packed and the effects of all worlds coming down is emphasized clearly. Also, hopefully the Crimson King get portrayed as the big baddie that he's supposed to be (or at least referenced more, he only was talked about very minimally in throughout the series and only showed up at the end). With Jake drawing pics of the Gunslinger and all, I think it's portraying that he somewhat remembers the Gunslinger from previous cycles(called Shine or something in the movie) Hopefully Roland remembers also cause the whole reason he has to go through this journey again and again is because of his character and how he would be willing to let others die so he could reach his goal. I'm hoping this movie ends with Roland and Jake on a beach and a door in front of them...ready to Draw the others.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
I hate to admit I'm a bit...mixed on this.  On one hand, despite some people here, I love the casting of Roland and The Man in Black (yes I'm totally fine with Roland being black, Idris Elba is one of the best actors in Hollywood).  I also really love the idea of this being a sequel of sorts to the final book (readers know what this means).  

However...the tone of this doesn't really match up with the incredibly grim, dark tone of the books.  This seems a bit too glitzy and show-offy.  I'm also not getting the impression that this is a hard R movie, which it absolutely needs to be, perhaps more than the vast majority of R-rated films to come out in recent memory.  The Dark Tower deals with absolutely grotesque themes, extreme violence, insanely vulgar dialogue and more than a healthy serving of sex and nudity.  Making it appeal to a more mainstream audience would be a deathblow, in my mind.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment: Ok so as a fan of the original book series, (as well as the ones that are tie ins, like insomnia, everything's eventual, hearts in Atlantis, etc), I can understand the frustration of some of the commentors. But there are a few things to keep in mind here. As for Roland being black in this movie, I too did have concerns because what ramifications would that have on Susannah's character since much of what made her who she was was an undertone of isolation being the not only the only female but also the only black member of their ka-tet. In this movie that's going to be a non issue since her character is not in it. Now whether this becomes a franchise & they eventually do more movies or not may change that. That being said, Roland is a rather difficult character to cast for & Idris is one of the few people whom can pull it off. So I think it's only fair to give him a chance. Additionally, you also have to remember, for those that really DID read the books, Roland has the horn of Eld in this movie. that is very important because the only point in which he has it in the books is when he is standing in the Mohine desert AFTER reaching the tower at the end of the 7th book. in the story arc of the books, the horn of eld was lost on Jericho hill & only returned to him at the end as he began a new cycle, immediately forgetting the last. this movie IS that new cycle. sure I wanted to see Eddie, Susannah, the people of Calla Byrn Sturgis, Callahan, Patrick Danville, even John Farson, all those people too. The raid on Algul Siento, Jake & Callahan storming the Dixie Pig, ol double ugly getting eaten alive by monstrosities, & maybe that is all still to come in future movies. or maybe that will be in a tv show format where honestly books tend to better translate to film anyway. however it's clear that this movie is not an adaption of the 7 cannon novels, but a continuation from where they ended. this movie is starting not at the the beginning of the gunslinger, (book 1) but at the end of the dark tower, (book 7). in short, new territory. So go into it with an open mind.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
There's definitely a few problems here in my opinion. My issue specifically is with the nature of the dark tower that is depicted in this. I feel like in the books it was something beyond comprehension, a constant thing in the background which drives everyone in the books almost to the point of obsession, the centre of everything that is. It just seems almost a little clich√© the way they depict it here, although It's just a trailer so that might be an early judgment. I also feel the series wasn't as focused on fight scenes as much as this, it was always sudden bursts of violence which almost shocked the reader. Obviously they have also smashed many parts of the book into one story which is a little disappointing but understandable because of the length the movie can't really do an epic like the Dark Tower series justice. 

I don't know what all the complaining about Roland is about though, Idris definitely got the feeling of the character, I don't think his race is really an issue. It's pretty refreshing actually, and if the movie is trying to keep a distance from the exact story of the books then it does make sense to change it up a little. To be honest I'm just happy that this will more than likely encourage a wider audience to get into the books. I feel they never really got the praise they deserved.

Hoping for some Lobstrosities tho, that would be great.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
Ok, so it seems that this entire movie will have nothing to do with the original story from the books. That is very disheartening, as I wanted to see that story be brought to life at some point. 
But it would at least partially explain why Roland is suddenly black, because the Dark Tower is basically holding the multiverse together and in one of those worlds, Roland could defintely be black. I'm ok with that now. 
But there's still a lot about this trailer that makes me fear that this will just be a run-of-the-mill overly stylised action movie which compresses too much of the mythology of TDT into an incoherent mess and is more concerned with over the top action-scenes. Gunslinger shooting without looking? One of the essential parts of the mantra Elba is reciting in this trailer is "I do not aim with my hand, [...] I aim with my eye". Gunslingers are great shots, but they aren't Jedi. Same goes for the silly mid-air reload.
I'm now willing to give this movie a chance, but my expectations after this trailer are VERY low. I do however like the eastereggs about other King works in the movie, and I think McConaughey as Walter/MIB and the actor they have for Jake are fitting for their roles.
I'm just still sad that they didn't try to adapt the original source material. I would've loved to see the original Ka-tet in action. Without Eddie and Susannah, there's just something missing.

Comment:
this isn't a direct adaptation of the books, but actually a sequel to them...  After Roland finally reaches the Dark Tower and faces off against a villain known as the Crimson King. It‚Äôs there that he discovers that he‚Äôs gone on this quest before, many times, and is sent back to the beginning of his journey by a being known as Gan each time. In prior quests, Roland had left the Horn of Eld with a dying compatriot after a battle. In this latest version of the quest, he kept it with him, which changes things for the next cycle of the story.

The implication here is that the film is set after The Dark Tower (the novel): Roland has been sent back to the beginning of his quest, and the events of The Gunslinger will play out in a slightly different way. As we saw in the trailer, he meets Jake Chambers, and is going after The Man in Black. So, the film could essentially be an adaptation of The Gunslinger, but a continuation of the story at the same time.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment: I understand The Dark Tower was in development hell for the longest time, and I understand this is a sequel to the books.  That being said, I am upset because I, and I'm sure many others, wanted an adaptation of the books.  Before anyone starts responding, just please hear me out.  I envisioned this story to be told in both movie and television formats.  That is a bit risky given the amount of material, but it can work.  Books 1, 3, 5, & 7 would serve as movies, with the 7th book being split into two movies.  There are five movies there.  Books 2, 4, and 6 would be adapted into three television series, preferably on HBO or Showtime.  There are three seasons there.  This would have to be filmed consecutively as LOTR was to account for the length of time the book series runs.  This is possible, and unfortunately Hollywood got their money-grubbing hands on a beloved series.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
This is a travesty. All I can say is, Stephen King, what were you thinking when you let this profound book series be turned into an Idris Elba gunshot reel? The Dark Tower is a sacred story, full of epic, dystopian cyber kingdoms and unforgettably acerbic protagonists (two of whom aren't even in this film) an allegory of modernization and ancient, occult magic that absolutely changed my life and the lives of the many individuals who chose to go on this journey with you.

And this is what we are supposed to accept as the film adaptation of this tale? A stale battle of wits between Idris Elba and Matthew McConaughey? I have seriously never been more infuriated at a trailer in my entire life.

I mourn this. I really do.

Comment:
As a black woman, I'm MUCH more upset about the removal of Susannah/Odetta/Detta than anything. Where are she and Eddie?! I can sort of understand the upset about Roland not being white, because there are SO many descriptions of him appearance on the book, and if Susannah and Eddie were in the story, it would change some of the dynamic (but only to an extent: if Stephen King is for it, I'm 100% cool with Idris Elba, he's an amazing actor.) I just don't understand how they could take something as fully-realized and laboriously descriptive as TDT series and relegate it to some big-budget sci-fi action blockbuster that takes FAR too little from the source. Why did they have to deviate so much, to the point where it's nearly unrecognizable? 
I'm probably still going to go see it, and I may even enjoy it... but it's not The Dark Tower.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
As far as character selection goes, while Idris Elba is a good actor, it is known to those who read the books that Roland Deschain was based on Clint Eastwood.   Clint Eastwood is old, he's 86 now.  A suitable replacement would be Viggo Mortensen.  He has the look, and he's a good actor.  Plus, he's 58 now, and the only time Roland was ever truly portrayed as young, was in memory flashbacks and in Wizard and Glass and in The Wind Through the Keyhole.  

And for everyone saying Roland was never truly portrayed as white, yes he was in Drawing of the Three when Detta referred to him as a Honk Mofa and also sensed his complete whiteness, and in The Dark Tower it was while he was with Irene Tassenbaum that it was further revealed that not only was he white, he may have had Native American blood as well.

And for everyone else saying it has already severely deviated from the books, yes it has!  It was supposed to!

https://twitter.com/stephenking/status/733244613000069120?lang=en

If you didn't actually get to the end of the books, you missed a major clue.  This is a continuation of the book series, and that has been acknowledged.  This is not a typical film adaptation.  This is using film to continue and hopefully conclude one of the best series I ever read, and what can easily be argued as the best work of Stephen Kings writing career.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
As a black man, I know that just because someone disagrees with a black actor playing a character that is written white doesn't mean they are racist!  Some are, but most just want to be true to the written word they have already experienced.  I love Elba and I think he is awesome but, i don't think he should be the next James Bond either.  James Bond is a white secret agent - always has been!  While he's a supporting character, not a main character, imagine they remade Rocky and made Apollo Creed white???  I know I'd be pissed!  Not because I'm a racist! Rather, Apollo was originally a black character - and I liked it that way.  I be pissed not because they chose a white guy.  More so that they changed the context of the story that I enjoyed.  
What really needs to happen is black writers need to come up with better story lines that will appeal to broader audiences.  This years "Get Out" is a prime example.  We have to figure out a way to get stories other than gangs, drugs and violence on the big screen.   Then black actors would have more prospects and opportunities to play interesting characters that are written for them. 
I know Hollywood is f***'d up but it can be done!
BTW - I'm gonna still see the movie because it looks interesting.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
I just spent about twenty minutes reading all the comments, just to get a better gauge on what other people's opinions on this trailer are, their insights into the discrepancies between the books and this film, etc, etc.  So I've read that people are considering it a "sequel-ish", being that time travel, teleportation and the ending of the literary saga allows for such things after Roland passes through the Tower Door.  But these don't really interest me as explanations, nor does this film being some amalgamation of Books 1, 5, and some new re-imagining that some Hollywood scriptwriters put together.  Seeing this just confirms my fears that I won't want to see something I've looked forward to, and that's not saying it will be a bad film, it's just not the film I want to see.  

This reminds me a lot of I Am Legend, since Hollywood has made that incredible story into a film three times, and all three were ok films, just ok at best; but they never seem interested in capturing the grit and horror of the book.  That's what this looks like, it looks like a good film for most people unfamiliar with the source material, but from what I as an insanely committed fan of the book series hoped for, I'm just not seeing it in this trailer, nor have I felt it when reading about the making of this film.  To everyone who see's it, I hope it's good and you enjoy it, but I just know I won't, so I just won't ever watch this.

The books will have to be my wealth spring, since it looks like Hollywood has miles to go yet, before doing this epic true justice.

Here's an excerpt from the original story:

"Jake opened his folder to take a final look at what he had written on the topic My Understanding of Truth.  He was genuinely interested in this, because he could no more remember writing his Final Essay, than he could remember studying for his French final.  
 He looked at the title page with puzzlement and growing unease.  MY UNDERSTANDING OF TRUTH, By Jake Chambers, was neatly typed and centered on the sheet, and that was all right, but he had for some reason pasted two photographs below it.  One was of a door - he thought it might be the one at Number 10, Downing Street, in London - and the other was of an Amtrak train.  They were color shots, undoubtedly culled from some magazine.
 Why did I do that?  And when did I do that?
 He turned the page and stared down at the first page of his Final Essay, unable to believe or understand what he was seeing.  Then, as understanding began to trickle through his shock, he felt an escalating sense of horror.  It had finally happened; he had finally lost enough of his mind so that other people would be able to tell."

However the tone and feel of this trailer seems way off from the books, like by allot. The books were always more character driven with allot of word building throughout. They tended to be a fairly slow burn with a couple of decent action scenes spread around, that's how it was in every book. The first book in the series, though it has been awhile sense I read it, only had like one big action scene in it, the one right at the start.

 This trailer seems to show off what looks to be a fairly generic action movie, and is way off from any of the books.
Hell, *Spoilers* don't read if haven't read the books yet, In the book Roland doesn't even go to our more modern world until the second book, and he didn't go there with the kid, and it was after he got his fingers on his right hand tore off, which then got infected, and he nearly died because of it.

I won't judge the movie based on the trailer, as I truly hope the movie is good, but if what I'm to expect from the movie is similar to what's mostly being portrayed in this trailer then I am going to be extremely disappointed.

Comment:
DARK TOWER BOOK SPOILERS AHEAD, AVOID: 

A lot of people are crying foul because SPE is turning this into seemingly another shoot'em up that doesn't follow the plot of the book and I am in that camp. I realized while discussing that with a friend that SPE has an out to soothe the rage of the people who have read and love the books: they can explain it away as another cycle of Roland's journey. Every time Roland goes through the door things change and it's inferred he's gone through the door many many times. SPE can just claim this is one of a near infinite number of cycles where things are just different from the one we read. If SPE is smart they'll add this, subtly, into the movie, in a way only people who read the books would really get.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment: This looks awesome!!! I love the books and I'm happy to see a gunslinger on the big screen.  I've read them soo many times.  Movies are not books and books are not movies.  When did a movie ever faithfully recreate a book?  Never.  It's not possible because the mediums are completely different and a movie is an artists interpretation of a book.  Much like how you may have envisioned Eddie or Susannah/Odetta when you read the books is not the same as how I envisioned them.  Stephen King has said that this is more like a sequel to the books than a film adaptation.  That's great!!! Keep the books pure and give us an additional part of the story.  Spoiler for those who didn't read the books, but the story goes on.  As the books say, "There are other worlds than these".  This world we see here is different than the world we know from the books.  It doesn't mean it's horrible or wrong.  Remember the end of the final book and the alternate world with "certain" people alive and well.  Indeed, there are more worlds than just the world we read about.

Comment:
There are going to be a lot of haters. I was a little miffed at first that they cast an african american actor to play Roland because he is so clearly described as a white man with bright blue eyes, but Idris Elba is a spectacular Actor. If you haven't seen Luther then you don't even know...
That being said - true fans of the books will let this slide. They know that this is not a direct adaptation but a sequel. And that many things can change on different levels of the tower -  and at different cycles (in the books 2 non-relative characters are blood brothers in a different version of New York so a families race changing is not hard to believe at all). I have no problem with it, and I for one, have gone from cautiously optimistic to overtly hopeful.
I mean look at it! We get to see Lud, River Crossing, Steven Deschain, it even looks like they didn't skimp on the Dutch Hill Mansion Demon afterall... 
Screw the haters. This movie is going to be awesome.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment: I always thought one of the coolest scenes in the book was when Eddie had to shoot his way out of a drug house butt-naked. That's courageous. But the entire Gunslinger mythos has always inspired me for some odd reason. To have guns that are forged from the swords of Arthur Eld, to wield them as the Gunslinger did, to have been raised in a culture where the Gun is the way of life...all of these things create an almost mystical world full of technology, dereliction and decadence from a time not entirely separate from our own. It's almost as though the things we've discarded have fallen through to Roland's world. It's where the pillars of our own universe--and many others--are firmly rooted. I don't know...I just feel like we're all looking for our own Dark Tower and some are more driven than others. And there are those of us who are driven to extremes that some would say border on lunacy. Whatever our Dark Tower might be--whatever it is we're looking for--sometimes we have to discard the things most precious to us to find it, to scale the stairs and to reach the top. I know Roland the Gunslinger lost a lot in the books. Love and sense of self being but two things out of many. He's seen a lot and he has a kind of 'frontier wisdom' that I hope comes through in this cinematic adaptation. I'm holding out for "Cool Blue Shooter's Eyes" such as Roland had in the book. Roland, for me, has become an archetype for one who has lost it all just trying to find his way in the world, utilizing skill sets that some of us may view as archaic but that in his world are indicative of an old and ancient nobility. The books got a little slow, at times, and were somewhat difficult to finish. But I did finish them. All the way. To the very End. Be careful what you make your Dark Tower out to be.

Title: THE DARK TOWER - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
Idris does make a decent representation of Roland. Unfortunately, the rest of it is a disappointment: no other companions in sight, Jake elevated to main character even if he was originally pretty much a deconstruction of what a child would really be able to do in a dark fantasy plot (that is, mostly just suffer), too much focus on New freaking York. King's trademark fascination with characters on the fringes of society and the dark American underbelly is all gone. Journey across a post-apocalyptic dimension with isolated quirky communes, gone. Heck, Eddie is gone. 

Instead, we get slo-mo gun kata. Boo freaking hoo.
